1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,540
Let's learn about NumPy and how we can use it to do this.

2
00:00:03,540 --> 00:00:09,390
NumPy is short for numerical Python and is designed for efficient scientific computation.

3
00:00:09,390 --> 00:00:12,135
It's built on top of the programming language C,

4
00:00:12,135 --> 00:00:14,850
which works at a lower-level on our computer.

5
00:00:14,850 --> 00:00:17,850
To understand what this means for the speed of our code,

6
00:00:17,850 --> 00:00:20,040
see the link in the instructor notes.

7
00:00:20,040 --> 00:00:22,575
Pandas is built on top of NumPy,

8
00:00:22,575 --> 00:00:27,195
which is why it's so fast with all its computations for functions like describe.

9
00:00:27,195 --> 00:00:31,895
If you try doing these computations in plain Python, it's much slower.

10
00:00:31,895 --> 00:00:37,280
Here's an example, calculating the mean for an array of 100 million values.

11
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:41,945
This generates an array of 100 million random floats zero and one.

12
00:00:41,945 --> 00:00:45,775
We could also type in 1e8 to make this clearer.

13
00:00:45,775 --> 00:00:49,430
Looks like that provides a float when it requires an int.

14
00:00:49,430 --> 00:00:53,880
Let's see how long it takes standard Python to compute the mean of this array.

15
00:00:55,540 --> 00:00:58,380
A little more than nine seconds.

16
00:00:58,380 --> 00:01:01,420
Now, let's see how long it takes NumPy.

17
00:01:02,270 --> 00:01:05,660
That was almost instant. Isn't that cool?

18
00:01:05,660 --> 00:01:09,830
Imagine how much it speeds up the process when there's much more computation happening.

19
00:01:09,830 --> 00:01:13,850
For example, let's say we're engineering a whole new feature or column,

20
00:01:13,850 --> 00:01:16,550
which you compute by multiplying the values and two columns

21
00:01:16,550 --> 00:01:20,270
together and divide by the values in another for each row.

22
00:01:20,270 --> 00:01:23,030
Unlike NumPy, plain Python would require

23
00:01:23,030 --> 00:01:27,505
a massively long loop through all the rows to compute the new value for each row.

24
00:01:27,505 --> 00:01:30,260
The main object we work with in NumPy is

25
00:01:30,260 --> 00:01:33,785
a multi-dimensional array of values of all the same datatype.

26
00:01:33,785 --> 00:01:37,100
These arrays, along with many useful functions in NumPy,

27
00:01:37,100 --> 00:01:40,890
optimize and simplify operations on data.

